sry idrk where u commented but I j wrote up the process

We decided to use the PE ratio method of valuation, where we used EPS data from NASDAQ for the fiscal years 2016-2022 and according share prices at the reporting date of each fiscal year's 10-K. We first calculated the EPS growth rate of each year starting from 2017, as the difference between the current year's EPS with the previous year, divided by the previous year. Then, we calculated the PE ratio of each year using share price divided by EPS. We then moved on to projections, with trailing PE from ZACKS of 51.82X and average EPS growth rate we took by averaging the EPS growth rates from 2017-2022. We calculated target price of fiscal year 2023 as trailing PE * estimated EPS * 0.9 to account for market corrections and be more conservative in our valuation. For fiscal years 2024 and 2025, we replaced the trailing PE in the target price formula with the previous year's target price. After calculations, we arrived at target prices of $301, $505, and $848 for fiscal years 2023, 2024, and 2025 respectively. We graphically represented our estimates through a line chart, showing projected steady growth for the forward looking fiscal years.
